text:
have you ever faced a problem that could only be solved by you solving it? that's every situation that you face in life. no one cares if you are having a bad day, if your parents were drug addicts, or if you were born with a disability. that's the truth and it may seem crass but it's not, it's just real. you have to figure it out.

we all have an immense amount of power inside of us that allows us to step into the person that we want to be. the only person stopping us is us.

do you agree with that?

now, since we know that we are the only person that can stop us, doesn't it make sense that we are the same person that can catapult us into health, happiness, success, and love?

it all starts with deciding that we are good enough, smart enough, and capable enough to have whatever you!

like if you agree.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
i was so honored to be able to attend 2019's trailblazer honors, a yearly event that recognizes pioneers fighting for justice for minorities in their careers.
this year, they honored four incredible women who not only inspire american women but everyone regardless of nationality, race, sex etc.
the honorees of this year were:
filmmaker ava duvernay, author margaret atwood, #metoo founder tarana burke, and speaker nancy pelosi!
with special performances from rita ora and elle king.
cher, anita hill, mindy kaling, alyssa milano, samira wiley, peppermint, aja brown and alysa liu shared the stage as presenters and sharing their stories!

amazing night! i was less than 20 meters away from them! i shared the same room and air with cher!

#trailblazer #vh1 #cher #nancypelosi #honors #womenpower #trailblazerhonors #awardsshow

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: do you ever feel like when you start to gain momentum something steps in and slows you down. well, last night i began to get super sick and woke up this morning congested. i decided to stay home and not hit the gym.  normally, this would derail my goal but by the end of the day i started to feel better and decided to head to the gym anyway! i could have said, naw it isnâ€™t my regular time so i will wait till tomorrow. instead i pushed past my excuses and went anyway! it is all about your choices. are you going to choose to give in, say i will do it tomorrow but that never comes or are you going to get back up and jump into the race again!!! i choose to keep going! i choose to stay in the race! what about you? do you have what it takes to make this life what you want it to be?  #takingbackmylife  #divorcedmom #iamworthit #downshiftology #motiv8performance #dropitlikeitshot #gymadict #nevergivingup #nevergoingback  #neverfail #ladybeast #hardworkpaysoffs #graciesjourney #goaldigger #motiv8aminos #ultimatefitness #eachonereachone #dontstopgetitgetit #paraeducatorsaredifferencemakers #everyonehasastory #youarewhatmakesithappen #teamalphamale #slimlifesolutions #sleevelife #girlwashyourface #girlstopapologizing #metoo #liveinthemoment

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

i was teased by boys at junior school for having braces ğŸ˜¬ â€œbrace-faceâ€, â€œmetal-mouthâ€, â€œtin-grinâ€, (yes to all of them). i was teased at junior school by boys because i developed later and didnâ€™t have â€œbigâ€ boob like some of the other girls in my class. .
i see some kids privately for yoga sessions & one mother asked me to chat to her child to see if anything was going on as she felt something was off. 
i always make it very clear to the child that yoga is a safe space to talk, i never push anything and i allow the child to share exactly what and how much they choose to tell me. 
nothing of significance came up and only at the very end of the session when i was rolling up my mat, did it emerge that maybe some boys were doing things that were just generally irritating and annoying and a â€œbit boyishâ€ .
my very first *conditioned* response to this was â€œoh. i was teased at school - thatâ€™s just boys! boys are boys!â€ but instead: i stopped. i took a deep breath and said - â€œi was teased at school too and we make too many excuses for boys - they need to take responsibility for themselves! in the mean time, we can focus on your worth - because when we have a strong sense of self worth - nothing and no one can take that away from you.â€ she agreed. â¤ï¸
and for the record, to those boys who teased me, iâ€™d like to let you know: my braces came off - i got beautiful straight teeth and beautiful boobs to match ğŸ’ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ (also:ğŸ–•ğŸ¾). .

text:
for years, americans have shrugged their shoulders over nsa surveillance and government access to digital data and said, â€œi donâ€™t care; i have nothing to hide.â€ now they are starting to see that maybe they do have something to hide. they are starting to understand that their own preferences and those of their friends and family can be hoovered up and stored in perpetuity and fed through algorithms to produce manipulative messaging intended to move beliefs and influence actions.

although regulators and state attorneys general are launching investigations, the real hammer will be the market. whether it is facebook, twitter, or some other social media platform, when users start to realize that the data they are sharing may be used against them or cause them to lose control over their beliefs or be manipulated, they will begin to shut off. if the company canâ€™t be trusted with personal data, users simply will not use that platform and advertisers will go elsewhere.

roger mcnamee, mark zuckerbergâ€™s long-time mentor, saw the risk early on and tried to get facebook executives to manage it, but his warnings fell on deaf ears.  in an interview with christiane amanpour, mcnamee said that in october 2016, he personally warned zuckerberg and sheryl sandberg of the magnitude of the risk, but failed to get their attention. according to mcnamee, facebookâ€™s leaders kept arguing that facebook is a platform company, not a media company and â€œweâ€™re not responsible for what third parties do.â€ mcnamee warned them then, - you have 1.7 billion members and if they decide you are responsible, it wonâ€™t matter what the law says.

jody westby

text:
without a shadow of a doubt this will be one of the best debut novels i will ever read, if not the best. it's truly astonishing that the bluest eye is a novel that began a literary career, yet in the foreword we find that toni morrison wasn't fully impressed. she says, regarding the stucture of the novel that "many readers remain touched but not moved," & though i may not be the most qualified to speak on any literary structure i can say that the story overall did move this reader & many others that have beared witness to the brilliance she exuded with this incredible story.

the bluest eye, set in toni morrison's hometown of lorain, ohio centers pecola breedlove. an 11 year old girl who is mistreated because she is dark-skinned & "ugly." she feels that if she gets blue eyes, like the white girls & women she sees on tv, advertisements, films, billboards, candy wrappers, & more then she will finally get the life & treatment she deserves.

although this novel is certainly about pecola, i also look at this novel as being about black women. a tribute in one sense because throughout the novel you witness the clear & unadulterated love morrison has for black women. the strength to endure that they have had to develop in a country that villifies them to no end. from slavery all the way to the present black women have been looked at as not good enough in the us. from their opportunities being minimized to domestic jobs where they had to clean up after white adults & children as if they were their own family, then to afterwards do the same for their own families & potentially receive mistreatment from a spouse, often a black male, who is often times taking out his frustration with the world on them. to even now where they can legally be discriminated against for wearing braids to work while non-black women get glorified for doing the same.

there are endless themes in this novel, but the sadly relevant theme that stuck out, especially in the era of surviving (you know who) & #metoo is the complicity of many communities in the harming of black women & girls.

we must listen, learn & do better by our girls. there is no other option.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
introducing our awlcrwanda2019 speakers
-
mary akpobome
-
mary akpobome is the chief operating officer of hbcl investment services plc, a private investments company. prior to her appointment to hbcl investment services plc, mary was the executive director, business banking overseeing all corporate, commercial, special projects, intervention schemes, multilaterals, agriculture and export businesses of heritage bank.
-
a fellow of the institute of credit administrators, mary holds an mba from the university of lagos and a bachelorâ€™s degree in theatre arts from the university of benin, edo state, nigeria. she is an alumnus of lagos business school, london business school and insead (france); mary has attended courses at stanford graduate school, harvard business school, kellogg executive education and well as imd (switzerland).
-
read full biography at https://awlo.org/awlc/speaker/mary-akpobome/

text:
when you are ignorant of the truth that you have been made bigger than the world, you always allow worldly factors determine who you are, what you do and where you'll be. 
but the scriptures says in 1john 4:17 that "greater is he that is in you than he that is in the world." the god who created the universe dwells in you. this means you are bigger than the cosmos. you are bigger than all planets. and the universe is an under-estimation of your power,  dominion and greatness.

when you have this understanding,  you determine the happenings in your life, with your words and faith you create what you desire to experience. you're no ordinary person.

text:
pernahkan teman-teman mengalami kejadian seperti gambar diatas? disiulin oleh orang yang dikenal ataupun tidak dikenal sehingga membuat kita merasa terganggu dan tidak nyaman?

jika pernah, maka mulai sekarang sebaiknya kita jangan diam saja dan menganggap kejadian tersebut sebagai
hal yang wajar. karena meski nampak sepele, disiulin merupakan salah satu bentuk pelecehan seksual yang paling sering terjadi di sekitar kita.

pelecehan seksual ialah segala tindakan/perilaku/gerak-gerik yang memiliki muatan seksual yang tidak dikehendaki sehingga menyebabkan rasa marah, perasaan terhina, malu, depresi, tidak nyaman, dan tidak aman bagi orang lain. pelecehan seksual bisa berbentuk verbal (kata-kata), non-verbal, tulisan, fisik, psikis, dan visual.

tindakan pelecehan seksual ini dapat terjadi karena cara pandang yang menempatkan tubuh orang lain sebagai
objek seksual belaka. pelecehan seksual dapat terjadi tanpa pandang jenis kelamin, namun dalam relasi kuasa
yang tidak setara dalam struktur bangunan masyarakat patriarkis
saat ini membuat perempuan menjadi lebih rentan terhadap hal tersebut.

pelecehan seksual adalah salah satu dari sekian bentuk kekerasan seksual dan dapat dikategorikan sebagai
kekerasan berbasis gender. oleh karenanya pelecehan seksual dapat digolongkan pula sebagai salah satu bentuk pelanggaran hak asasi manusia.

pelecehan seksual ialah segala tindakan/perilaku/gerak-gerik yang memiliki muatan seksual yang tidak dikehendaki sehingga menyebabkan rasa marah, perasaan terhina, malu, depresi, tidak nyaman, dan tidak aman bagi orang lain. pelecehan seksual bisa berbentuk verbal (kata-kata), non-verbal, tulisan, fisik, psikis, dan visual.

tindakan pelecehan seksual ini dapat terjadi karena cara pandang yang menempatkan tubuh orang lain sebagai
objek seksual belaka. pelecehan seksual dapat terjadi tanpa pandang jenis kelamin, namun dalam relasi kuasa
yang tidak setara dalam struktur bangu masyarakat patriarkis
saat ini membuat perempuan menjadi lebih rentan terhadap hal tersebut.

pelecehan seksual adalah salah satu dari sekian bentuk kekerasan seksual dan dapat dikategorikan sebagai
kekerasan berbasis gender. oleh kareya pelecehan seksual dapat digolongkan pula sebagai salah satu bentuk pelanggaran hak asasi manusia.

text:
pernahkan teman-teman mengalami kejadian seperti
gambar berikut? disiulin oleh orang yang dikenal ataupun
tidak dikenal sehingga membuat kita merasa terganggu
dan tidak nyaman?

jika pernah, maka mulai sekarang sebaiknya kita jangan
diam saja dan menganggap kejadian tersebut sebagai
hal yang wajar. karena meski nampak sepele, disiulin
merupakan salah satu bentuk pelecehan seksual yang
paling sering terjadi di sekitar kita.

pelecehan seksual ialah segala tindakan/perilaku/gerak-gerik
yang memiliki muatan seksual yang tidak dikehendaki sehingga
menyebabkan rasa marah, perasaan terhina, malu, depresi,
tidak nyaman, dan tidak aman bagi orang lain. pelecehan seksual bisa berbentuk verbal (kata-kata), non-verbal, tulisan,
fisik, psikis, dan visual.

tindakan pelecehan seksual ini dapat terjadi karena cara
pandang yang menempatkan tubuh orang lain sebagai
objek seksual belaka. pelecehan seksual dapat terjadi
tanpa pandang jenis kelamin, namun dalam relasi kuasa
yang tidak setara dalam struktur bangunan masyarakat patriarkis
saat ini membuat perempuan menjadi lebih
rentan terhadap hal tersebut.

pelecehan seksual adalah salah satu dari sekian bentuk
kekerasan seksual dan dapat dikategorikan sebagai
kekerasan berbasis gender. oleh karenanya pelecehan seksual dapat digolongkan pula sebagai salah satu bentuk
pelanggaran hak asasi manusia.

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
it was a sweltering may afternoon last year. lying on my roof, my friend @lily_raptor and i were working, in a near-sun stroke fomo-induced effort - it's london, and the planet is dying, you don't know how long this sun is going to last. enjoy.â£
but anyway, i had invited her for a lyric-writing session. as we were chatting, about things and others, the conversation veered towards feminism, as it usually did. we were at the height of the #metoo movement; the week before, h. weinstein had turned himself in to the ny police on sexual assault charges. we wondered what song would sing a lisbeth salander as she's getting ready in the morning, before sitting in court against her abuser. this is what came out.â£
i really wondered whether this song would still be relevant today. sadly it is. i do believe a shift has happened though. even though it's had little impact on most of the important people accused of abuse and/or assault - some might have (temporarily) lost their job, (temporarily) lost some reputation, but that's about the worst it got to - i do believe it will get harder and harder for people to get away with it. but aside from the dramas happening in the high spheres of society, i also do believe it's made us reach a critical mass, a realisation of the power we have in numbers, a number that makes it safe(r) to stand up and say "you think i'm gonna let you get away with it? think again. i'm not alone."â£
honoured that @getinherears have gone and premiered my song "bring your alibi" a day ahead of its release. link in bio âœ¨â£
thank you mari lane for the kind words ğŸ–¤â£
â£

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
#ynaijanewestablishment: jekein lato-unah makes the ynaija new establishment list .
jekein lato-unah (visual arts/advocacy) .

many people discovered jekein unato through her controversial interviews with the renowned social media documentary project humans of new york, lato-unah was one of the few people hony has given two opportunities to speak on their stories and jekeinâ€™s work as a visual artist and activist were highlighted. .
lato-unah is a professionally trained visual artist and part of a vocal wave of feminists who choose to adopt a dual pronged approach to feminism, engaging in exhaustive online conversations about the politics of the body and how interrelationships between the genders can be improved and offline activism through female owned and run non-profits like stand to end rape (ster), sanitary aid for nigerian girls (sang) and the market march. .
.
unato was one of the first women to facilitate a social media driven #metoo drive, encouraging teenage girls to speak up about the abuse they had suffered in their secondary schools. she is also a vocal advocate for consent and sexual health. .
.
unatoâ€™s work as an artist is also celebrated and she has participated in a number of exhibitions including the empowerment by creative debuts & nasty women exhibition in london, the magic of lagos group exhibition at the waterside in ikoyi, two group exhibitions at the omenka gallery and the wafflesâ€™nâ€™cream friends and family exhibition.

i am free!

text:
meet our congress chairperson
-
h.e chief dr. jewel howard-taylor
vice president of liberia
-

chief dr. jewel howard-taylor is a liberian politician and the current vice president of liberia. she was married to president charles taylor and was first lady of liberia during his presidency. in 2005, jewel taylor was elected to the senate of liberia in bong county as a member of the national patriotic party. she is the chairperson of the senate health and social welfare committee on gender, women and children.
-
while her husband was president, taylor held a number of official posts in the liberian government, including deputy governor of the national bank of liberia (forerunner to the current central bank of liberia), president of the agriculture cooperative and development bank (acdb) and mortgage financing underwriter of the first union national bank. in addition, she focused on educational health and social projects.
-
read full biography at https://awlo.org/awlc/speaker/jewel-howard-taylor/

text:
i sat listening to headlights by eminem, and restlessness took over me. everything about this song hits close to home. i catch myself thinking of every moment when i looked over my shoulder to see fathers playing with their daughters, laughing along. everytime that i went to a friend's house and saw them talking, as though there were no consequences. i remember wondering if they could be my father. i wonder if i'd be the person i am if i had that. if i'd have the same fears. if i'd look for the love he couldn't give me in others. or the safety. it's hard to talk about him, or to him. my father's demons were birthed with me, they live in me. i wish i could forget those conflicted nights when i  sat beside my mother, my hand on her forehead, gently trying to fix the bruises left, with my tiny incapable hands. or running away with her at cold nights, barefoot. or being on the run. or hating myself as a child for not being able to take care of my family on my own. i wish i could  forgive him. i wish i wouldn't be scared of every loud voice because it reminds me of 7th grade. i wish i could stop loving sharp objects on my skin, because it reminds me of him grinding his pencils on my skin. i wish i loved him enough to not get up in the middle of the night, and feel the weight of his foot against my neck. i wish i could i forget that and a hundred more. everytime i think about him i hear nate's voice singing eminem's verse -
"and to this day we remained estranged and i hate it though, but
i guess we are who we are
headlights shining in the dark night i drive on
maybe we took this too far"
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
â€œwhy iâ€™m a feministâ€
ğŸ§¡. itâ€™s a personal story. itâ€™s the story of so many of the things that have happened to me that showed me where my rights arenâ€™t equal. where the world has been constructed for the privilege of men. where my body is not considered my own. where iâ€™ve been penalized for being a woman, a mom. where the expectations of being nice anyway have cornered me and silenced me. where i knew something felt wrong but no one taught me it wasnâ€™t okay. ğŸ§¡. iâ€™m really proud of #metoo, but a lot of ugly things can hide beneath the hashtag. you know there is pain under there, but unless the story is told, you can avoid seeing itâ€™s horrors. so i told my story. ğŸ§¡
as yet, every single woman i have shown this to has said yes, she could tell a similar story. every woman. and many of them have been matter-of-fact about it. think about that. this is systemic at an incredibly huge level. it happens to all of us, all the time. death by a thousand cuts. ğŸ§¡.
while this work is my story, i think the real story is that so many of us can tell a similar one. it breaks my heart, yet fires me up to fight, to vote, to speak up. ğŸ§¡.
iâ€™m an artist. art is one of my languages, so i speak up here. we have used embroidery for centuries to learn our letters but also to teach our stories. so i used my needle to write mine. ğŸ§¡. made in 2018. digitally designed and hand embroidered by me. quilted by my dear friend @nstovall of @justquilting. and honored with 3rd place in the handwork category at quiltcon 2019. 
#quiltcon2019 #whyimafeminist #huntersdesignstudio

text:
#topicalthursdays 
it has been over 2 weeks since several young kenyan women came out with testimonies documenting predatory sexual behaviour by a popular kenyan youth pastor. in the same time span, several male gospel musicians have been accused of sexual assault. as is often the case in many â€˜news-worthyâ€™ incidents, the uproar seems to have been drowned out with little to no follow up on the side of law enforcement or the media. #metoo was a movement created to give voice to women to speak out against all forms of sexual violence. looking at its failures in being universally adaptable, the cases mentioned above show how power takes different forms depending on the region. in kenya, activism must incorporate a critical look towards religion and how misogyny continues to stifle female congregants. we stand with all the victims who have come out and those that are yet to find a voice to speak of their traumas. we are also watching keenly to see if any action is taken up by the kenyan government as had been earlier reported. women are more than second class citizens and they too deserve justice. check link in bio for an insightful article on africa and the metoo movement.

#metoo #womenrights #intersectionalfeminism #africanfeminism

text:
rape culture word choices:

can we discuss the phrase "credibly accused "? i''d like it if reporters made them explain what criteria that meets. which boxes are checked off.

i was reading an article (like 50 a day) and a rcc representative was saying that if a priest etc received a single report of abuse, they file it and unless there isn't a second report by a separate person about a separate assault, they simply...file it away.

now. we all know, pedophiles don't just hurt one child. statistically, we know this. evidence based research suggests that a predator harms upwards of dozens of kids before "getting caught" (the numbers fail me, it's early). and imagine, most reports of abuse result in getting caught!!! but not soo much it seems at institutions like the rcc.

you can't take a report or suspicion sexual abuse and file it away, folks. hoping it will resolve itself or someone else will do the right thing on your behalf. not how accountability works.

so read this article. and then remember yesterday where the pope, this constitution's top dog, said that anyone who spends their time accusing the church is the same family as the devil. ****i don't think the devil has been sitting on lists of thousands and thousands of names of pedophiles....on payroll. but you know who does??? the roman catholic church does!

text:
reviewer's name: srividhya iyer
book: #metoo brutus 
author : prana natarajan (dyrt member) 
genre :fiction
self published

i was happy when the author prana natarajan pinged me asking if i can review his debut book. thanks pn for having the confidence in me and asking me to review your book. "#metoo brutus" is a catchy title. really appreciate the author in having given a good thought about the title. we all have heard/read  the #metoo stories going around in social media. this book is also about similar #metoo incidents that happened in the recent past, all woven into a nice story. 
the story is about few characters and their #metoo situations. one a studious girl and how her dreams are shattered, a mother getting abused by godman, another small town studious girl facing a #metoo situation and how she took a bold step to get the culprit under the law, another professional facing a #metoo situation at work place, a small girl facing a #metoo situation with godman. all these stories have a interwoven secret and the author has surely kept that as a suspense till the last. 
the other part of the book also speaks about how each of the #metoo victims deal with it and if the culprits are punished or not. 
being an indian background story a minister,a political power, sure does have an important role in the book. which is yet another surprise element in the story. 
the last bit of the story is an eye opener with awareness information. 
enjoyed reading the book and being a debut book the author has done a fair job. he already has his second manuscript ready and eagerly waiting to read that too. 
as of now available in kindle. rest of the details author prana natarajan,  can share with us. 
happy reading ğŸ™

text: " each time you are able to use a timbo "empowered resource", you create a new memory for your reference library. think of this library of implicit memories as a jar of blue marbles. the blue marbles are all of the memories created by way of your early life experiences, and reinforced by your adaptive responses and behaviors. in any given circumstance we pick a blue marble (memory/reaction) that drives our habitual response. but when we practice these these embodied resources we have a new outcomeâ€”even if that outcome is that we chose to breathe or to compassionately talk to our inner critic instead of any number of things that we would habitually do. each new experience becomes a new memory (letâ€™s say new memories are green) and replaces an existing blue marble. the jar is still primarily full of blue marbles, with just one or two green ones which makes choosing to use an embodied resource some work at first. this is often the reason i get calls and texts from women like ruthie, or when women in our community reach out to our facebook group for support. they simply need to be reminded of their new tools. over time more green marbles replace blue ones and eventually our new empowered resources become our implicit memory. the work simply dissolves and what we have left is a new way of being in relationship with ourselves and the world around us." #trauma #traumarecovery #resilience #wellness #yoga #mindfulness #women #selflove #selfhelp #recovery #community #healing #metoo #men #authorsofinstagram #adversechildhoodexperiences #writersofinstagram #womenempowerment

text:
george mendonsa, the united states navy sailor made legendary with dental assistant greta zimmer friedman for their kiss in alfred eisenstaedt's famed "v-j day in times square" photo taken in new york city on august 14th 1945, has unfortunately died 4 days ago at the age of ninety-five. rip to the sailor who with friedman easily helped capture the feelings of many americans following their victory over the japanese empire in world war il, and may both mendonsa and friedman be remembered in american history forever.
-
-
today, the statue of the famous image in florida has been vandalized with the words "#metoo" written in red spray paint. recently, the image had become controversial in that mendosa was accused of sexually assaulting friedman in the photo. in a 2005 interview, friedman said the kiss was non-consensual, but that she understood it was a â€œjubilant actâ€ and that she did not view it negatively.
-
-
-

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

the guardian

skyhigh atop of the llyn peninsula, on the slopes of yr eifl, the iron age hillfort tre'r ceiri, meaning "town of the giants". one with the ancients in the land of my father's. @decsperring
was boudicca here?
where's boudicca now?
don't mess with boudicca, she was the first #metoo
rumor has it boudicca was in wales, she was of course a celt, but at the time when  the hillfort settlement was at its largest, was around the start of roman occupation, when boudicca and fellow celtic tribes were uprising against the romans, so perhaps her surviving tribesmen fled here, east to west.
her husband was the iceni king an ally of rome, when he died, leaving his lands divided between his wife and daughters and the emperor nero, the romans flogged her and raped her daughter's for presuming they had rights which should be recognised by rome. boudicca was quick to organise an uprising, her east anglian iceni tribe sacked the romans capital of colchester then destroyed st albans and london massacring 70,000 romans to the shame of the empire. one savage act was to cut off the breasts of noble women and sew them to their faces, and impale them on skewers. inevitably in battle retribution was served, boudicca was confident she was delivering the final blow to the romans, but supposedly nearly 80,000 britons fell in a massacre, with only 400 roman deaths. for a time, legend had it boudicca was buried under platform 10 at kings cross station, presumably jk rowling's inspiration for platform 9 and 3/4. @officialjkrowling

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
it's been a while since you've been acting weirdly. be it at our meet ups or on our routine calls, you seem to be quite lost and i ain't liking it. i'm missing the shrill you because this softer version is not the one who i fell for. okay, it's good that you have started contemplating, thinking out hard, talking way to mature stuffs for your like but don't you think that i was assigned for that part? you were supposed to utter total gibberish and i was supposed to laugh and get annoyed at the same time but now it's not the same anymore. sometimes you talk, sometimes you opt to stay quiet and stare at the quaint surrounding. this silence is deafening!

sometimes i feel that you do want to tell me what's actually bothering you but i don't know why you end up swaying away from the point. i know it's tough, i know you love me, i know you're way too concerned about me being bothered about you but honey, don't you get that you being secretive about your problems, kills me more. life will strike you bad, beat you, torture but never do you forget that you got me. under the brightest aura of sun's might and and the shine of the moon's halo, be it the best of light or darkest night, baby, you got me.

come to me, yell at me, scream as much as you want but talk to me. put your head on my lap, wrap your arms around my waist and speak your heart out. cry if you want to, howl as much as you want, i won't stop you. it's you and it's your way of healing but let it begin through me. let the world judge you, but you're none to break because remember, everytime you're about to fall, you'd find me as the cord, firming your spine to face everyone. don't be afraid of showing your true colours because that's why i love you.

sourav dey| select writer.
(@quill_and_paper)
.
.
.

text:
one of the toughest things my mom and i have gone through in therapy is reading the words of my abuser and trying to get me to get them out of my head. i've learned that the ptsd i suffer from now and the anxiety i feel every time i'm forced to be around him is because i have been so bullied that i am physically and emotionally sick.  his constant taunts and cruel words have rooted into my spirit. its debilitated me and it makes me infantile and causes me to self medicate by either running away or by getting very depressed.  the court has made me have to call him, the man who sodomized me, to contact my children. its impossible because everytime i do he sends me evil evil messages, calls me a "loser", tells me i'm "fat" "worthless". these are the types of messages he sends me. he takes me to court or separates me from my children if i dare to complain. it's a vicious cycle that i'm committed to changing in the best interest of my children. i am not a "cunt" dr. james orsini. i am the mother of your three children. if the state of new jersey doesnt call you out for your crimes against all decency, i will. i'm starting today. 
i am also an instagram author and a boston university college of communcations grad. #proudmom #metoo #findawayormakeone

the issue of virginity arises mostly at the time of marriage and after, but not before. we live in a society where girl is being asked by a boy mostly that is she a virgin or not when marriage talks happen. no one in this whole world has given any man or any one else right to ask a girl about being virgin. just because her hymen is broken already doesn't mean she has been in a physical relationship with someone else. it's proven biologically that it may happen while doing sports and physical training. and to be very honest such kinds of taboos related to virginity are less in cities as compared to villages. the only way to make them realise is through sex education and campaigns.

text:
yuk kita berani melawan pelaku pelecehan!
â€¢

jika memungkinkan untuk kamu berani merespon cepat pelaku pelecehan, ada beberapa tips untuk melawan tindak pelecehan:

jangan diam: tunjukkan ketidaksukaan kita terhadap tindakan yang melecehkan, bisa dengan teriak, melotot, membentak atau mendatangi pelaku dan sampaikan
ketidaksukaan kita. hal itu juga bisa menjadi sarana penyadaran bagi pelaku, bahwa tindakannya itu melecehkan. jika tidak memungkinkan, kamu bisa berlari menjauhi pelaku dan menceritakannya pada orang lain.

ketika di kampus, seringkali kita beraktivitas hingga malam hari, sehingga ketika pulang, jalanan atau gang sudah sepi. untuk berjaga-jaga kita dapat membawa peluit, semprotan cabe, atau semprotan lain seperti parfum.

jika terjadi tindakan seperti dihadang ditengah jalan atau dipeluk paksa secara tiba-tiba kita dapat merespon dengan menyemprotkan semprotan cabe/parfum ke mata pelaku, meniup peluit untuk meminta pertolongan, pukul, tendang ataupun serang balik pelaku dengan barang bawaan kita (tas, sepatu, buku dsb). â€¢

text: â€œinfinite jest is just awful. it seems ridiculous to have to say it. he canâ€™t think, he canâ€™t write. thereâ€™s no discernible talentâ€¦ stephen king is cervantes compared with david foster wallace. we have no standards left.â€ legendary literary critic and yale professor harold bloom pulled no punches when asked about david foster wallace (dfw), and there seems to be a growing number of critics and fans who subscribe to the same belief. they point to his maximalism and meandering sentences; his overly verbose and oed-inspired wordage; that his writing often feels unnecessarily cerebral, self-important, and pretentious; and underneath all of this window-dressing are boring stories. what drew me to his writing (and kept me as a reader through the thousands of pages of output) was his humor, his marriage of high- and low-brow, his ability to make the esoteric and the mundane seem important and entertaining, and his uncanny ability to feel like the voice in my head. this collection of short stories, excerpts from novels, nonfiction essays, and material from the courses he taught, is an overview of the prolific writerâ€™s career and showcases his ability to craft sentences into a multitude of forms without a dip in quality. while the styles may differ, thereâ€™s a thread that connects the lot, with similar themes written with tonal uniformity. ten years on since i first stumbled upon his work and i continue find myself in awe of sentences he crafted, with emotions stirred and feelings that resonate deeply within me. i have read infinite jest twice, a book that spurred on my entrance into recovery from my alcoholism, and reading these passages for a third time was still wildly entertaining and insightful and beautiful and haunting. and yet, it was not age or maturity or any existential change that led me to view this collection in a new light. reading anything by dfw after 2018â€™s #metoo movement [continued in the comment section]

text:
testimony of my friend valkryie:
my name is valkyrie weather, born kyle cohen, the oldest child and trans daughter of film producer/director rob cohen (the fast and the furious, xxx, and the hurricane heist among many others). when i was very young, rob used my body for his own sexual gratification. my mother witnessed one of the assaults when i was between two and two and a half years old, and has since confirmed what she saw. this fact has cost me more than i could ever convey here. rob has also raped at least one other woman, in her sleep. i know this because he would occasionally tell the story as an anecdote. presumably in an effort to turn me into the straight son that he wanted me to be, rob took me to see sex workers and establishments in thailand and the czech republic starting when i was as young as 13/14 years old. through therapy and support from loved ones, i no longer feel that i owe this man any loyalty. and thanks to theÂ #metooÂ movement, i have found the will to speak out. while rob will in all likelihood escape criminal justice, i demand that my story be heard. i am not seeking financial restitution, nor do i have a career to promote. my greatest hope is that others who have been hurt by rob cohen feel that they are able to come forward as well.
#hollywood #losangeles #thefastandthefurious #miamivice #movies #producer

text:
which criteria do we use to decide if a bank is good or bad? ğŸŒğŸ’¸ one of the indicators to evaluate whether a bank contributes to a better society is the percentage of assets used to grant loans to individuals and companies. in this case, banks members of the global alliance for banking on values @bankingonvalues (53 international ethical and sustainable financial institutions) based in europe (23 of these banks) in 2017 destined 77% of its assets to loans, while the traditional european banks only allocated 40.52%, according to the â€œreport on finance and ethical banking in europeâ€œ recently presented at the european parliament.

another traditional indicator to measure the impact of banks is their performance in terms of return on equity (roe). in this case, members of the global alliance for banking on values have a return on equity of 3.98% compared to 1.23% of traditional banks.

in addition to these indicators, the most important thing is to analyse whether a bank has a positive social and environmental impact, and according to this,Â  the banks of the global alliance for banking on values are again the winners over traditional banks.

during this week the global alliance for banking on values celebrates its 10th annual summit in vancouver (canada) under the titleâ€œmigrants, #metoo and melting icecapsâ€œ, showing clearly the purpose of this group of banks; contribute to the great social and environmental challenges of society. this network of ethical and sustainable banks covers the five continents, having ethical banks in countries such as the united states, australia, malaysia, uganda or peru.

text: survivor story: sydney was thrilled when her law firm sent her to europe for a couple weeks to attend meetings at their offices abroad. after a long day she went to the hotel gym to workout. when she was alone on the treadmill, a stranger tapped her on the shoulder. when she turned around she saw a man with his face covered who held a knife to her throat. he said if she screamed he would kill her. she froze in terror as he proceeded to force himself on her and rape her. he quickly fled afterwards while she laid on the gym floor in shock. sydney eventually made her way back to the hotel room. she said she was flooded with self-loathing. asking herself â€œwhy didnâ€™t i try to fight?â€ â€œwhy did i freeze?â€ she was horrified someone from her law firm would find out, she felt like  they would judge her or think she was weak or did something to cause it. she didnâ€™t know what to do. the firm has an eap, counseling and an emergency number to call but she was so afraid to disclose the rape to anyone in her firm. sydney remembered seeing a presentation about pathways to safety international. she found the information on the internet and called internationally toll free.Â she spent three hours on the phone with a case manager. the case manager listened while she told her story and talked to her about the options guaranteeing sydney confidentiality and anonymity if that is what she chose. she knew she did not want to make a police report but needed to get prophylactics. the case manager arranged everything for her including transportation and a translator while staying on the phone with sydney the whole time. that was three months ago. sydney still calls her case manager almost every day. they helped her navigate a horrible experience in her life while she was abroad and after she returned to the usa. today, sydney is seeing a counselor locally but says her case manager at pathways has been her lifeline. her case manager has been with her every step of the way. *names/images have been changed to protect survivors identity. #gethelpnow #endsexualviolence #metoo #endsexualassault #europetravel #iamasurvivor

text:
as i saw these petals falling down, this thought of temporary people came up to me. 
we all know that not everyone in our lives will not stay forever. 
falling apart from each other like there were no strings attached, is one of those strangest things i've ever came across. 
i do believe in this theory of â€œtemporary peopleâ€ because i've experienced it. 
and personally i believe that if someone wanted to go let them go. but, if someone wants to stay, hold their hand and say that â€œ i'm always by your sideâ€. this sentence will make things and feelings easier to understand. .
.
. 
ps: again trying to be a photographer!! .
.
.

text: #love #kindness #throwbackthursday  when i went to visit my mother for xmas, i volunteered to sing for the patients at this medicare facility for seniors, where my mom volunteers every sunday. i was grateful to be able to bring a little joy in their lives that day. and i love how they sang along w/ me during â€œyou raise me upâ€(swipe - second video) ğŸ™ before i got sick, i was a professional oboist. thatâ€™s where my doctor title comes from; i got a doctorate in music from usc. i used to sing and write songs and perform them at venues around la. i produced an album thatâ€™s still available on itunes called elegie under my artist name ginnicide (so emo i know but my music was not. i was 25 and â€œironicâ€ ğŸ™„ğŸ˜‚). i wrote, produced, and acted my one-act musical loosely based on a #metoo experience in college. but after my illnesses going through chemo, all the medication, and being bedridden for 2.5 years, my voice changed. i canâ€™t hit the notes as clean as i used to and my range is a lot smaller. itâ€™s funny, after i sang this to the patients (swipe last photo), my mother said to me w/ tears in her eyes that she was sad how my voice wasnâ€™t the same and a waste it is. i understand where she is coming from and i can only imagine the pain of what a mother feels after watching her daughter go through so much and i thought i did a pretty good job considering everything! iâ€™m grateful that i was able to sing from my heart to them ğŸ’›ğŸŒŸğŸ™iâ€™m grateful to my hubby for recording this moment. i am grateful for how far i have come in my healing. maybe my voice will never be the same and itâ€™s beautiful in itâ€™s own way. it shows my journey and just how much the #medicalmedium knowledge has helped me in my healing, including all of the other things i did to help me on my path. there was a time when i used to be so angry about having to quit my career and those creative outlets bc of my illnesses and now i am so grateful and humbled for everything that i achieved and experienced. i had a lot of really cool experiences as a musician and iâ€™ll always have those memories w/ photos, concert programs and itunes as proofğŸ˜‚ i move forward w/ new hope and aspirationsğŸ™ #vulnerable #honesty #healing
name: Dr. Ginny Orenstein

text:
walking along piccadilly today, i was forced to turn back as the pavent was closed, so i tried to cut through st james' churchyard, which i've passed many times, with its market out front. what i discovered behind was a beautiful garden and this caravan, offering free counselling. i have been wondering about access to therapy and counselling so much recently, as i have been fortunate enough to be able  to finance/access therapy myself- and posted about it just two days ago, so it felt  serendipitous to find such a hopeful, kind and accessible service. 
i hope to discover more services like this out there. as well, of course, as more state funding for therapy and support. #mentalhealthawareness  #mentalhealth #mentalhealthfunding #metoo #london
